Denote  (\frac{1+\sin{\theta}}{1-\sin{\theta}}-(\frac{1-\sin{\theta}}{1+\sin{\theta}})=T, then
T\cdot\frac{1+\sin^2\theta}{1-\sin^2\theta}=\frac{2}{1-\sin^2\theta}.\end{think}
We have \begin{align*}T&=\frac{2}{1-\sin^2\theta}\\&=(1+\sin^2\theta)(\tan\theta \sec\theta)\\&=\tan\theta \sec\theta\end{align*} and the equation $\tan\theta \sec\theta=1$. The answer is 1.                                                             <thesis>Done</thesis>
